{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660062"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22757"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22757"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111929"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15704"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22757"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93993"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"120"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45696"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111929"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a six month history of a painless swelling in the right side of the scrotum.\u00a0 The practitioner will now examine the swelling to determine its cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph shows the first step in the examination (Image 1). The swelling is now clearly on display (Image 2). Further definition is provided (Image 3, 4).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the swelling?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inguinoscrotal hernia","Varicocele","Epididymal cyst","Hydrocele","Seminoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sequence of photographs shows how a scrotal examination should be performed. The examination of any bilateral structure will start with an examination of the normal side. This is not shown here as it has already been done and the normal features determined. The examiner has approximated his thumb and index finger above the swelling (and palpating the vas) (Images 1, 2), thus assessing that the swelling has arisen from within the scrotum and is not an \u003Cstrong\u003Einguinoscrotal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E. The right testis is now palpated and the examiner is able to feel it and get his fingers between the testis and the swelling (Images 3, 4).\u00a0 The swelling arises from the superior aspect of the testis.\u00a0It is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eepididymal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the swelling was a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E, the testis would not be felt as a distinct entity. The testis itself would be enlarged if the swelling was a \u003Cstrong\u003Eseminoma\u003C/strong\u003E. In addition, a testicular tumour would be an unusual occurrence in a patient in this age group. A \u003Cstrong\u003Evaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a dilatation of the veins in the pampiniform plexus, would not be so visible and would compress during the examination.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epididymal cysts can usually be diagnosed on clinical grounds alone and most do not need any formal treatment."],"references":["Langan RC, Puente ME. Scrotal masses. Am Fam Physician 2022 Aug;106(2):184-9. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2022/0800/scrotal-masses.html","O\u0027Kelly F, McAlpine K, Abdeen N, Keays MA, Guerra LA, Leonard MP. The futility of continued surveillance of epididymal cysts - A study of the prevalence and clinico-demographics in pre- vs. post-pubertal boys. Can Urol Assoc J. 2019;13(12):E398-E403. doi:10.5489/cuaj.5667"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93993"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22757"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22057"},{"type":"media","id":"22058"},{"type":"media","id":"22059"},{"type":"media","id":"22060"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22057"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/oYPei6hVaL1LswxSMlk67Jpd35yHO1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/oYPei6hVaL1LswxSMlk67Jpd35yHO1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"22058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22058"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SBLzZVu0FaCFXvAulygZ9MFpjNG02Z.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SBLzZVu0FaCFXvAulygZ9MFpjNG02Z.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"22059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22059"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MTJGHVtKdWROBmeuZPBQw9iJbl0SfG.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/MTJGHVtKdWROBmeuZPBQw9iJbl0SfG.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"22060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22060"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1WNRXtDrVZr3YyklWxeawBlVgiBxUF.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1WNRXtDrVZr3YyklWxeawBlVgiBxUF.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93993"},"attributes